==English==
{{was wotd|2007|March|8}}
{{wikipedia}}

===Alternative forms===
* {{l|en|portmantua}} {{q|only in the sense "travelling case"}}

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|en|/pɔːtˈmæn.təʊ/}}
* {{a|US}} {{enPR|pôrtmă'ntō|pô'rtmăntōʹ}}, {{IPA|en|/pɔːɹtˈmæntoʊ/|/ˌpɔːɹtmænˈtoʊ/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-portmanteau-1.ogg|Audio 1 (US)}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-portmanteau-2.ogg|Audio 2 (US)}}
* {{audio|en|en-au-portmanteau.ogg|Audio (AU)}}

===Etymology 1===
{{bor|en|fr|portemanteau||coat stand}}, from {{m|fr|porte||carry}} + {{m|fr|manteau||coat}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun|s|portmanteaux}}

# A large [[travel]]ling [[case]] usually made of [[leather]], and opening into two equal sections.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1667|author=Charles Croke|title=Fortune's Uncertainty|passage=Rodolphus therefore finding such an earnest Invitation, embrac'd it with thanks, and with his Servant and '''Portmanteau''', went to Don Juan's; where they first found good Stabling for their Horses, and afterwards as good Provision for themselves.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1859|author=Charles Dickens|title=The Haunted House|passage=He brought down with him to our haunted house a little cask of salt beef; for, he is always convinced that all salt beef not of his own pickling, is mere carrion, and invariably, when he goes to London, packs a piece in his '''portmanteau'''.}}
# {{lb|en|Australia|dated}} A [[schoolbag]]; often shortened to ''port'' or ''school port''
# {{lb|en|archaic}} A [[hook]] on which to [[hang]] [[clothing]].

